{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513989"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:17:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:17:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12259"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12259","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12259"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.48,0.16,0.01,0.04,0.32]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4781"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56269"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4781","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4781"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12259"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41822"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1590"},{"type":"tags","id":"1598"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7629"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8364"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8886"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35598"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43311"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44375"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56269","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56269"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year-old man is admitted to the General Medicine Unit due to functional decline complicated by COVID-19 infection (confirmed by PCR). He has a 2-day history of shortness of breath, dry cough, general malaise, and loss of appetite. His history includes hypertension, hypercholesterolaemia, and chronic back pain from L4/5 disc herniation. He takes perindopril and panadeine forte regularly.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he is alert and oriented to person, time, and place. His blood pressure is 140/90 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, pulse 89/min, SpO2 95% on room air, and temperature 37.9\u00b0C. His chest is clear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis laboratory investigations show:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHb: 130 (135-175) g/L\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWCC: 21.1 (4.0-11.0 x10^9/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPLT: 120 (150-400 x10^9/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECr: 68 (60-110 \u00b5mol/L)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Nirmatrelvir plus ritonavir (Paxlovid)","Dexamethasone","Baricitinib","Tocilizumab","Remdesivir"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAll available options are appropriate therapies for COVID-19 infection but they are used for different severities of infection. It is important to keep in mind that research in the treatment of COVID-19 infection is rapidly changing, and it is vital to check your hospital or region\u0027s guidelines for the latest up-to-date detail.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn a patient with COVID-19 infection, the oxygen saturation goal is 94% on room air or above (provided they have no pre-existing alternative oxygen saturation goal, e.g. patients with CO2 retention often aim for 88-92%).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENirmatrelvir plus ritonavir (Paxlovid)\u003C/strong\u003E is the first-line treatment for mild COVID-19 infection in patients at high risk of progression to severe disease. This patient does not require supplemental oxygen and has very minimal respiratory signs, hence meets the criteria for mild COVID-19 infection, which makes nirmatrelvir/ritonavir the preferred medication.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAntivirals for COVID-19 are recommended for individuals deemed to be at high risk of developing severe disease. Individuals are eligible for PBS funded medication if they are within one of the below high risk groups:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eare 70\u00a0years of age or more (can receive the treatment even if they are asymptomatic)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eare 60 years of age or more, and have at least one other risk factor for severe disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eare 50 years of age or more, and have at least two other risk factors for severe disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eare Aboriginal or Torres Strait Islander, are 30 years of age or more, and have at least one risk for severe disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eare 18 years of age or more and have moderate/severe immunosuppression or immunocompromise.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERisk factors include the following: residential care, disability with frailty/multiple comorbidities, neurological conditions, chronic respiratory disease, heart failure, kidney failure, cirrhosis and living in remote areas with limited access to medical care.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERemdesivir\u003C/strong\u003E is an intravenous medication and it is used in hospitalized patients with moderate COVID-19 infection who are not on mechanical ventilation. It can also be used in patients with mild COVID-19 infection who may have a contraindication to nirmatrelvir plus ritonavir.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDexamethasone\u003C/strong\u003E is used in patients with moderate COVID-19 infection who require supplemental oxygen or ventilatory support. If dexamethasone is not available, it is reasonable to use other glucocorticoids at equivalent doses. This patient does not have an oxygen requirement and so dexamethasone is not indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBaricitinib\u003C/strong\u003E is an option for patients requiring high-flow oxygen or noninvasive ventilation and for patients who are on low-flow oxygen but are progressing toward needing higher levels of respiratory support despite the initiation of dexamethasone.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETocilizumab\u003C/strong\u003E is used for individuals who require high-flow oxygen or more intensive respiratory support. It is recommended to use tocilizumab on a case-by-case basis as an option for patients on low-flow oxygen supplementation if they are clinically progressing toward high-flow oxygen despite initiation of dexamethasone and have significantly elevated inflammatory markers (e.g., C-reactive protein [CRP] level \u226575 mg/L).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Nirmatrelvir plus ritonavir is the first-line oral treatment for mild COVID-19 infection in patients at high risk of progression to severe disease.","In a patient with COVID-19 infection, the oxygen saturation goal is 94% on room air or above (provided they have no pre-existing alternative oxygen saturation goal, e.g. patients with CO2 retention often aim for 88-92%)."],"references":["RACGP - Prescribing workflow [Internet]. Racgp.org.au. 2018 [cited 2022 Nov 16]. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/covid-19-resources/clinical-care/oral-antiviral-treatments-for-covid-19-br-prescrib/prescribing-workflow","South Australian COVID-19 Clinical Management Guidelines. COVID-19 Treatment Recommendations for Hospitalised Adult Patients. Version 4.5. November 2022.","South Australian COVID-19 Clinical Management Guidelines. COVID-19 Antiviral Treatments Guidelines and Resources.","Pathology Queensland. \u0022Understanding Your Pathology Results - Common Tests and Normal Ranges.\u0022 Queensland Government. https://www.health.qld.gov.au/clinical-practice/guidelines-procedures/nursing/understanding-pathology-results/norm-ranges.","RACGP. Oral treatments for COVID-19 \u2013 Prescribing information for GPs - Paxlovid (nirmatrelvir plus ritonavir). RACGP. N.d. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/clinical-resources/covid-19-resources/clinical-care/oral-antiviral-treatments-for-covid-19-br-prescrib/paxlovid-nirmatrelvir-plus-ritonavir","Australian Government Department of Health and Aged Care. Eligibility for oral COVID-19 treatments. Australian Government. 2024. Available from: https://www.health.gov.au/health-alerts/covid-19/treatments/eligibility"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41822"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12259"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41822","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41822"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-19T21:52:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-19T21:52:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4781"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56269"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Disease